The signing amount surpassed the INR 16 crore that Delhi Daredevils paid for Yuvraj Singh in 2015 - the previous record for a player signed at the auction.The Royals entered the bid battle only at INR 10.25 crore mark after Mumbai Indians appeared to have wrested Morris from his previous employer - Royal Challengers Bangalore. The Jaipur franchise had to contend with another new bidder - the Punjab Kings - who entered at INR 13.50 crore and went all the way until INR 16 crore before pulling out.The 33-year-old Morris has previously been a part of Rajasthan Royals, in the 2015 season when he scored 311 runs and took 13 wickets from 11 games. In all, he has played 70 IPL games and scored 551 runs at a strike-rate of 157.88 and taken 80 wickets at an economy of 7.81. Morris was an integral member of the RCB side last season even though an abdominal injury curtailed his participation to nine games. He took 11 wickets at an economy of 6.63.
